  footnotes: []
english:
  title: In Response to Park Jigyeong's Poem, Presented to An Gyeomjae
  author: Baek Mun-geo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    They say the new year brings many auspicious signs—
    Blessing and glory gather in a noble household.
    The old ancestral dwelling, modest and austere,
    Has transformed into the hall of a refined scholar.
    How foolish I am, with my thinning white hair,
    Yet charmed by the dark brows of the singing girl.
    Give me, I ask, a crystal cup in hand
    To wash away the turmoil of a lifetime.
  footnotes:
    - The poem is written in response to Park Jigyeong's work, following the same rhyme scheme as a form of literary exchange.
    - The contrast between the speaker's age and attraction to youth—white hair and dark brows—reflects a common theme in East Asian poetry exploring the passage of time and enduring human desire.
    - The 'crystal cup' (玻瓈盞) is a precious vessel, symbolizing both material luxury and spiritual purification through wine.
